&%d  

Cold, wet and tired. Just another day in the office, I guess.

The hours might be terrible, but look at all the interesting people you meet.

Well. Former people, anyway.

I don't see anyone around. Do you see anyone?

Nope. Nobody living, anyway. We're alone out here. 

Good. I guess we're free to do... whatever it is we do.

That's us. Consummate professionals.

*Yawn* Sorry. Bit tired.

You'd think after all this time you'd be more of a night person.

Don't worry. I'll muddle through. 

Somehow.

Let's get a move on. I'm running low on coffee.

Heaven forbid.

Let's get a move on. Maybe it'll be warmer inside.

Working on it.

I've seen pictures of condemned buildings, but I never thought I'd be in one.

Well, you're here. I just hope you had all your shots.

It's weird to think. This building's going to be knocked down once we're done.

Once we clear out the spook, yeah.

So next year, there could be a bank or a drug store here or something.

Could be. So let's enjoy these luxury surroundings while we can.

Looks like people used to live here.

Yeah. Whatever happened, they sure cleared out fast.

Let's keep looking around. I don't want to spend more time here than I have to.

Right behind you.

It's funny. There are hundreds of stories about haunted churches.

And here I am, actually bringing a ghost to a church.

Great. I'm a floating cliche.

I can't believe I was arrested. You think it's on my permanent record?

Does it matter? They already got a file on you.

Great.

It's hard to believe a house like this costs as much as my tiny room in the city.

Thinking of moving?

God no.

You really feel it? The cold? I thought you couldn't feel things like that.

Some kinds of cold go beyond physical, sweetheart. Whatever happened here is one of them.

Nice job getting that computer to work. I'm impressed.

Impressed? All I did was blow on a hunk of plastic.

Even still. You used a computer. You'll be tweeting next.

Eh? I don't even want to know what you mean by that.

I love the look of these old brownstones.

Really? These were old even in my day. I never understood the appeal.

They're... solid, I guess? Secure. People like that in a home. It's comforting.

Comforting. Really. You feel this way, too?

Kind of. We see death all the time, Joey. Isn't it nice to see something that lasts?

Eh. Not really. All it does is remind me of how old I actually am.

Joey. I'm already freezing. Do you have to make me depressed, as well?

You're the one who brought it up.

Poor Emil. Kendra is dead and he has no idea.

Don't tell him. Not yet. He won't believe you, and we might still need his help.

As nice as this place is, I can't stop thinking about George and Lia. About what... happened.

I know. Just try and focus.

It's cold. It's really cold out here.

So go back inside. I ain't stopping you.

I can't remember the last time I went to a gym.

Thinking of joining?

With all the walking I do every day? I don't think I need to.

We don't have a lot of time. We need to get to Madeline.

I always used to wonder what it would be like to go to this school.

Never thought it would take... this.

It's so quiet.

Just the calm before the storm. Let's end this before it gets here.

Two days ago I went to a drug den. Today I'm visiting a prostitute.

And you say we never go anywhere interesting. 

You think they'd have coffee in a place like this?

Only with whiskey in it. Maybe.

Well, here we are. Stuck in an alley next to a dumpster.

First class all the way. That's us.

I don't care if we get caught. I'm just happy to be warm.

Let's just do what we need to do and get outta here.

Funny that we've never been to a graveyard before. I mean, considering.

Not really. Spooks generally avoid thinking about death.

But in a place like this? It's hard to think about anything but.

We got here just in time. Look at her. She's tearing herself apart.

Normally I'd say good riddance. But I guess we gotta stop her.

So how much does shilling for the cops pay these days?

I don't know. Does it matter? It's not like we have a choice.

And I'm not shilling. I'm consulting.

Whatever looks good on the business card, sweetheart.

You think you've had enough coffee? One more cup and you'll start vibrating.

This coffee is a medical necessity.

And what do you call the four packs of sugar?

I call it shut up.

You warm enough in that coat? I don't think I could deal with you getting another cold.

I'll try to spare you.

Come on. We're on the clock.

How'd a squathole like this last so long in this neighborhood?

Gentrification is a slow process, but pretty soon old buildings like this won't exist anywhere.

And this is a bad thing?

How're you holding up? Any warmer in here?

Not really. This place isn't exactly well-maintained.

A coat of paint, maybe some new rugs, a plant or two...

Nah. It would still be a dump.

Come on. We won't get anywhere if we keep jawin'.

Yeah, yeah.

I've never been much for praying.

But after last night...

I'd pray forever, if I thought it would help.

We'll get to the bottom of it, Joey.

Yeah. That's what we do.

Have I already said that I don't like working with the police?

Not in the last ten minutes.

Well. I don't like working with the police.

Not a bad neighborhood, I guess. Quiet.

Maybe. Astoria's nice but I wouldn't want to live here.

Can't picture yourself doing yard work or cleaning the gutters, huh?

That, and the nearest cafe is ten blocks away.

Huh. Lucky escape.

This place. Something is wrong.

It's freezing. I know that.

Yeah, but it's... not just the cold. It's something else.

Something else? Like what?

Believe me. I wish I knew.

You walked right in here like you owned the joint. I don't think that desk guy even blinked.

He was half-asleep and more interested in his computer screen than me. It wasn't exactly hard.

You sound almost disappointed.

The streets sure are quiet tonight.

Not really surprising. I wouldn't be out either, if I had the choice.

Poor guy. He seems pretty bitter about things, but it's hard to blame him.

A nice cozy home like this, you gotta ask why George would leave it to go out in a blizzard.

He was looking for us. He thought we could help him. And Lia.

Yeah. Well. Let's try and make it worth something.

A roof deck like this, I wonder if money actually can buy you happiness.

I'll settle for central heating.

You wanna get a few rounds in while we're here?

I'm not exactly dressed for the gym, Joey.

Excuses, excuses.

How desperate does a spook have to get to pull the crap that Maddy's pulled?

Desperate enough to destroy a city by the sheer force of will? I hope I never have to find out.

This place was around even in my day. You ever go here?

No. It's one of the more expensive private schools in the city. Not really an option for a foster kid like me.

We didn't start this, but we sure as hell as gonna end it.

Let's get to Madeline before it's too late.

I guess you can't get over that fence, huh?

In this weather? No. This one is all yours.

This place looks like it was falling apart even back in my day.

Really? You think it's that old?

You doing okay? You're looking a little...

Freezing? Yeah. Thanks for noticing.

Let's do what we need to do and get outta here before someone sees us.

Man. I hate places like this. Let's just do what we need to do and get out of here.

Look at her. She's barely holding herself together.

No. She's trying to force herself apart. We need to stop her.

What am I supposed to do? Sing to it?

Does it want a hug?

Boy. If I could touch it, that would sure be great.

I can't touch it.

Dunno what I can do with it.

Can't do anything with that.

What do you want me to do? Blow on it?

What do you want me to do? Scare it?

Must I define intangible?

Ghost, remember? No touching.

I guess there's nothing stopping me from doing that, except for my nearly complete lack of physical existence.

Give me just a second. I'm going to add that to my list of Things I Cannot Touch.

There's a reason why I keep my hands in my pockets. There's less disappointment that way.

I love the idea, but I'm not really a hands-on kind of guy.

That's way too heavy for me to pick up. Then again, so is a pencil.

Nope. Still a ghost. Still can't pick that up.

I just can't come to grips with it.

He doesn't even notice the cold.

Better get her inside before she's as blue as I am.

Look at him. He doesn't even notice the cold.

Yep. He's still there. 

It's Red. Who else would it be?

I know it's cold outside, but I wish she'd get a move on.

Still Joey. Still following me around.

He keeps glancing up at the church.

I wish she'd get a move on.

I'm getting her back. One way or another.

He looks... edgy. I don't think he likes being here.

Yep. It's her.

He keeps looking at Durkin and frowning. I don't think he likes the detective much.

Why is she just standing there? No wonder that cop thinks she's crazy.

He doesn't look happy. I don't think he likes that I'm working with the police.

I can't believe she came back here after nearly getting thrown in jail.

He doesn't look too impressed with the place.

She's looking around the room and sighing. Jealousy, maybe?

I've never seen him so focused. I think he's taking this one personally.

There's a porch at least. She can take shelter there.

Is her breathing sounding a bit off? Hard to tell. Hope she's not getting a cold.

He looks pretty confused. After all this time, I've given up trying to teach him about this kind of stuff.

I hope she's not thinking of buying any of this crap. The last thing she needs is another gizmo to stare at.

Breaking and entering is just a normal day at the office when Joey's around.

Hopefully she can do more with that computer box than I can.

She's just standing around. Piling up snow.

She tracked wet snow all the way up the stairs. 

She keeps looking at that flashing gadget.

I can barely see him through all this snow.

I shouldn't stare. Not in public, anyway.

She's just standing there. Dripping water on the floor.

He looks a bit ill. I don't think he likes being near that circle.

Poor kid. We finally meet another medium and it's this guy.

He looks ready to finish this. So do I.

She looks a bit... unsteady. Hopefully it's just the hospital drugs wearing off.

Joey never looks comfortable around technology. This place is no exception.

She's looking wistfully around the room. Probably thinking about the road not taken?

He keeps looking through the gate at the ghost.

Hope she's warm enough.

He's still there. He's always still there.

Hope she keeps her hands off the booze. We need to keep focused.

Damn Joey and his not being able to feel cold.

Why'd she leave her coat inside? She's gonna die of frostbite out here.

She looks like she's beginning to thaw off.

He keeps looking at those photographs.

She's just standing in the hallway. Leaving wet footprints on the floor.

Yep. Still Joey.

He looks on edge. I don't think he likes being in places like this.

She doesn't look nervous to be here. I suppose it says something that this isn't the spookiest place we've ever been.

I don't know how, but I think he helped bring me back.

No time to thank him yet, though. We need to get out of here.

We need to get her out of here.

First thing is to get her some proper clothes. She wouldn't last two minutes outside in this weather.

She looks a bit unsteady. I guess with everything that's happened, I can't blame her.

I've never anyone so angry.

Of course, find me a mirror and maybe that will change.

She looks exhausted. Poor kid.

Karth House

The Karth House seems to be an old hotel that's been condemned for years. Detective Durkin asked us to meet him here. As for why, he didn't say.[[So far, he's a no show.

Detective Durkin

Detective Durkin helped us out with a case earlier this year. He doesn't know who we are, but he knows enough not to ask questions.[[He occasionally asks us to consult for him.

Cast and Crew

Downloaded a file that contains a list of all the cast and crew members for every performance that the Gotham Collective put on.

The ghost on the third floor of the Karth House is named Mary.

Gotham Collective

We found a photograph of the ghost on a memory stick. The photo was an actress's headshot, and the words "Gotham Collective" were written on it. A theater company, most likely.

The River Wall

A theater performance put together by the Gotham Collective. Mary was a cast member.

Drug raid

A newspaper article described a drug raid at a condemned building in Chelsea. Several drug addicts were found and an unidentified woman was found dead.

Murdered man

We saw a man murdered last night, and his ghost was torn apart right in front of us.[[No mention of the murder in the news. Perhaps the police know something?

Grace

The murdered man last night said the name "Grace", and that she wasn't safe.

Lia

In a prayer written by George, he hoped to save himself and somebody named Lia.

Inside Lia Pierro's house, we found the spirit of a little girl named Kendra Haskins.

Abacus

Kendra's father works at a place called "The Abacus". He is apparently the boss there.

Emil Haskins

Emil is Kendra's father, and Lia's ex-husband. He lives in the East Village in a building called the "Exeter House."[[He seems genuinely distraught over what's happened.

Trollgate

Kendra was a fan of an online game called "Trollgate."

Michael's #

A man named Michael called George Ostin the night he was killed.[[He called from the number 212-555-3412.

Gabriel Ullman

Father Gabriel Ullman is a priest at Grace Church.

Grace Group

When I spoke to Lia, she said that she was part of a self-help group that met in the basement of Grace Church. She called it the "Grace Group."

Michael

George received several emails from someone named Michael.[[Whoever this Michael is, he appears to know a LOT about what's going on.

Jeffrey Dutta

George Ostin received an email from someone named Michael.[[In the email, Michael wrote that he saw Jeffrey's soul being ripped apart.

George Ostin received an email from someone named Michael.[[In the email, Michael wrote about someone named Peter who died recently. Michael is worried that Peter might have encountered "the same fate" as the others.

Jeffrey, Peter, and Heather

George Ostin received an email from someone named Michael. In the email, Michael asked if George knew where Heather was. There was no answer.

Michael Cooper told us that a Japanese man named Benjiro ran the Grace Group meetings.

Roof ghost

We found the ghost of a woman on the roof deck outside of George's apartment. She seems to live - or rather, LIVED - in the apartment next door.

Heather's ghost asked Joey if "Ray sent him."

Jim Peebles

Jim is a producer at Channel 11. He works on the show that Tanya Corsey used to host.

Client list

I have a list of all of Ray's clients.[[There are... quite a lot of them.

Peter's number

Peter Fielding's ghost gave us his phone number. It's 646-555-0425, for all the good it will do us.

Connor Fielding

Peter and Maggie's father is dead and buried in Greenwood Cemetery. He died over twenty years ago on March 18th, 1993. Maggie doesn't want to talk about him.

Maggie Fielding

Maggie is Peter Fielding's sister. She is living in Peter's apartment.

Case #

The probation ID number for the woman living in Peter's apartment.

Karth File

The police case notes on the Karth House arrests.

